'''Molly E. Holzschlag''' (born January 25, 1963<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.molly.com/2005/01/25/birthday-girl/ |title=Birthday Girl |first=Molly E. |last=Holzschlag |date=January 25, 2005 |periodical=molly.com (via archive.org) }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>) is a US author, lecturer and advocate for the [[Open Web]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.molly.com/about/ |title=About Molly |first=Molly E. |last=Holzschlag |date=November 26, 2011 |periodical=molly.com}}</ref> She has written or co-authored over 35 books on web design and open standards, including ''[[The Zen of CSS Design]]: Visual Enlightenment for the Web'' (co-authored with [[Dave Shea (web designer)|Dave Shea]]).

She has been named one of San Francisco Webgirls' ''Top 25 Most Influential Women on the [[World Wide Web|Web]]''<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.sfgate.com/technology/specials/1998/01/webgrrls2.shtml |title=San Francisco Webgrrls in SFGate |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |author=Amy Moon |year=1998 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/20110930094339/http://www.sfgate.com:80/technology/specials/1998/01/webgrrls2.shtml |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref> and has worked with [[Microsoft]], [[AOL]], [[eBay]] and the [[BBC]] "promot[ing] standards and best practices to create highly sustainable, maintainable, accessible, interactive and beautiful Web sites".<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.amazon.com/Molly-E.-Holzschlag/e/B000APGWPC |title=Molly E. Holzschlag (author) |periodical=Amazon.com}}</ref>

==Campaigning for web standards==

Holzschlag is a very active speaker on Open Web technologies, web design and accessibility.<ref>{{citation|url=http://lanyrd.com/profile/mollydotcom/past/speaking/ |title=Molly E. Holzschlag (speaker profile) |periodical=Lanyrd.com}}</ref> She was the 2004–2006 group lead for the [[Web Standards Project]] (WaSP),<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.webstandards.org/about/members/mollyeh/ |title=Molly Holzschlag (WaSP member) |periodical=The Web Standards Project}}</ref> a coalition that campaigned browser makers such as [[Microsoft]], Opera and [[Netscape]] to support modern web standards. She would later join Opera as an open and accessible web evangelist.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.molly.com/2009/02/13/i-am-an-opera-singer/ |first=Molly E. |last=Holzschlag |title=I Am an Opera Singer |periodical=molly.com (via archive.org) }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

She currently participates as a [[World Wide Web Consortium]] (W3C) Invited Expert on the [[CSS Working Group]],<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.w3.org/Style/CSS/members.en.php3 |title=Members |periodical=Cascading Style Sheets working group}}</ref> chairs the [[CSS]] Accessibility Community Group<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.w3.org/community/cssacc/ |title=CSS Accessibility Community Group |periodical=W3C Community and Business Groups}}</ref> and was previously an Invited Expert on the HTML and GEO Working Groups.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.molly.com/about.php |first=Molly E. |last=Holzschlag |title=About Molly |periodical=molly.com (via archive.org) }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

==Teaching work==

Molly currently works for [[Knowbility]], for whom she teaches classes on Open Web technologies such as [[HTML5]] and [[WAI-ARIA|ARIA]], with a strong emphasis on using inclusive design to overcome [[accessibility]] barriers.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.knowbility.org/v/staff-detail/Molly-Holzschlag/7c/ |title=Molly Holzschlag (Knowbility staff) |periodical=Knowbility}}</ref> She has also taught webmaster courses for the University of Arizona, University of Phoenix, New School University, and Pima Community College.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.paperplus.co.nz/author/Molly-E-Holzschlag?i=180354 |title=Molly E. Holzschlag: Biography |periodical=Paper Plus}}</ref>

